The ministry said 346 of the new patients were Kenyans and 20 foreigners, 236 male and 130 female, the youngest a year old and the oldest 78.
Nairobi recorded 142 of the cases, Kiambu and Samburu 42 each, Murang'a 26, Narok 20, Kirinyaga 15, Embu 12, Mombasa 10, Kajiado eight, Nakuru, and Busia and Garissa six each.
Meru and Makueni recorded five each, Machakos and Kilifi four each, Uasin Gishu, Kitui, Mandera, Marsabit, Taita Taveta and Kwale two each, and Kakamega one.





The coronavirus disease was first detected in Wuhan, China, on December 31, 2019 and first confirmed in Kenya on March 13.
By December 13, 967 of Kenya's patients had been admitted to hospitals countrywide while 6,583 were under home-based isolation and care. 
CS Kagwe said 48 of them were in intensive care units, 28 on ventilator support, 18 on supplemental oxygen and two under observation.
